{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_9","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,220p' .workflow/iphone-app-factory/spec.md\"","aggregated_output":"# Product Spec\n\n## Research Evidence\nThe core problem targeting the \"chronic oversleeper\" is that snoozing has become an involuntary reflex rather than a deliberate choice. Users report that willpower-based strategies fail because executive function is impaired during the wake-up window. Research indicates that existing alarm apps (like Alarmy or Puzzle Alarm) suffer from a \"habituation decay\" – users memorize puzzles or discover workarounds, bringing effectiveness down drastically within 2-4 weeks. Furthermore, static difficulty leaves users frustrated (puzzles too hard when sleep-deprived) or bored (puzzles too easy). The core required solution is dynamic task rotation, escalating difficulty based on snooze behavior, and reliable multi-modal challenges (motion, cognitive, memory, environment).\n\n## User Journeys\n\n1.  **The Standard Wake-Up:** The alarm fires locally at the scheduled time. The user's screen wakes. They cannot easily swipe to dismiss. They are presented with a randomized challenge (e.g., a math puzzle). They must actively solve it within a timeout window to stop the noise. After solving, a \"wake confirmation\" is scheduled 5 minutes later to ensure they have not returned to bed.\n2.  **The Snooze Penalty:** The alarm fires. The user attempts to ignore it or uses a minimal interaction to delay it. Upon the next activation, the app has escalated the friction—switching to a physical 'Shake' requirement with double the normal required threshold, forcing physical movement.\n3.  **The Setup & Adaptation Route:** A new user configures their baseline difficulty, preferred tasks (e.g., opting out of math but keeping pattern matching), and schedules their alarm. Over days of usage, the app tracks their \"snooze rate\" and automatically adjusts the baseline difficulty up or down to find the \"Goldilocks\" zone of friction.\n4. **Social Accountability (Opt-in):** If the user repeatedly fails to wake up or utilizes the emergency escape hatch too often, an automated notification is sent to an opt-in \"social witness\" (friend/partner) to enforce external discipline.\n\n## MVP Scope\n*   **Alarm Engine:** Reliable local notification scheduling (must operate fully offline when firing). Custom, high-contrast, looping audio tracks. Timeouts and automatic re-triggering.\n*   **Challenge Modules (Rotating Modalities):**\n    *   *Motion:* CoreMotion framework shake-to-fill UI.\n    *   *Cognitive (Puzzle):* Math equations (dynamic complexity) or pattern matching.\n    *   *Environment:* Barcode/Location scanning (e.g., scan toothpaste barcode).\n    *   *Audio/Memory:* Voice confirmation or tap-sequence reproduction.\n*   **Dynamic Engine:** Task rotation (preventing the same task appearing consecutive days) and Snooze Escalation (increasing required interactions/difficulty if snoozed).\n*   **Safety & Accessibility:** \"Escape hatch\" UI (long-hold overrides for genuine emergencies) and accessible alternative inputs for physical constraints.\n*   **Post-Wake Confirmation:** A silent/haptic ping 5 minutes after alarm dismissal requiring a single active tap to prove the user is awake, preventing fallback-sleep.\n*   **Optional Social Witness:** A privacy-first notification capability to alert a designated contact upon repeated persistent failures.\n\n## Boilerplate Reuse\nThe application MUST forcefully leverage the `SwiftAIBoilerplatePro` repository. Rebuilding core infrastructure is strictly forbidden.\n*   **Auth/Data:** Do NOT rebuild authentication or persistence. Use the boilerplate's provided data layer and models.\n*   **Networking/AI:** Use the boilerplate's networking abstractions and AI integration points if needed (though the core alarm mechanic should function offline).\n*   **UI/Design System:** Utilize the boilerplate's foundational UI components (buttons, typography, layout containers), localization handlers, and settings screens.\n*   **Payments/Store:** Rely on the provided purchase/subscription configurations. We build *on top* of the framework.\n\n## Design Direction\n*   **High-Contrast & Urgent:** The UI must be immediately readable to blurry, sleep-filled eyes. High WCAG AAA contrast (e.g., bright yellow/orange on deep black). Large, legible typography (SF Pro Display).\n*   **Haptic Interface:** Heavy reliance on iOS CoreHaptics. Every interaction, shake threshold, or failed puzzle input should provide distinct, aggressive physical feedback.\n*   **Minimal Chrome:** When the alarm is firing, there should be zero navigational chrome. Just the task, a prominent timeout warning, and the loud auditory response.\n*   **Battery/Privacy Transparency:** Explicit UI conveying that motion/camera sensors are *only* active during the alarm event, addressing background battery drain concerns.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n1.  **Alarm Reliability:** Alarms trigger exactly on schedule using local `UNUserNotificationCenter` and function fully offline.\n2.  **Task Imperative:** Alarms cannot be dismissed via standard notification swipes; task completion must govern the dismissal state.\n3.  **Rotation & Escalation Logic:** The engine must enforce shifting task modalities across consecutive days and demonstrably increase the difficulty coefficient upon a snooze action.\n4.  **Wake Confirmation:** 5 minutes post-dismissal, a system-level notification requires user interaction; failing to interact restarts the primary alarm sequence.\n5.  **Overrides Function:** Accessibility fallbacks and emergency stop hatches function properly (and log the failure).\n6.  **Boilerplate Compliance:** Zero redundant implementations of auth, payments, AI, storage, networking, localization, or settings.\n\n## Appium Exploratory QA\nThe application MUST be validated mechanically using Appium/XCUITest.\n*   An exploratory \"monkey-tester\" framework must boot the application and programmatically attempt to click every reachable, enabled button and control in the available UI (settings, task configuration) to prove zero-crash stability.\n*   The test suite must programmatically simulate triggering an alarm condition and successfully interact with at least one task module (e.g., inputting a math answer via UI automation) to verify view hierarchy accessibility identifiers.\n\n## App Store Readiness\n*   **Guideline 4.3 (Spam) Differentiation:** The app metadata (Title, Subtitle, Description, promotional text) must heavily index on its behavioral psychology mechanics: \"Adaptive Difficulty Task Rotation,\" \"Post-Wake Confirmation checks,\" and \"Social Witness Protocols.\" It must explicitly differentiate itself from simple utility alarm clones. An automated string audit must verify these concepts are present.\n*   **Privacy Nutrition & Permissions:** The `Info.plist` must contain perfectly accurate usage string declarations for Camera (`NSCameraUsageDescription`), Motion (`NSMotionUsageDescription`), and Microphone (`NSMicrophoneUsageDescription`), heavily emphasizing that sensor data is *only* utilized within the brief active alarm window and never stored or transmitted.\n\n## Definition of Done\nPlease see `.workflow/iphone-app-factory/definition-of-done.md`.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_10","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,260p' .workflow/iphone-app-factory/architecture.md\"","aggregated_output":"# WakeTask Architecture\n\n**App**: WakeTask (com.keen.waketask)  \n**Date**: 2026-05-14  \n**Boilerplate**: SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro-Distribution  \n**Mission**: spec-kitty `waketask-iphone-app-01KRJRAF`  \n**Consensus of**: `architecture-codex` + `architecture-claude`\n\n---\n\n## 0. Bootstrap & Acquisition\n\n`apps/waketask-iphone` starts empty. Before any WakeTask-specific code is written, the boilerplate is acquired:\n\n```bash\nnode scripts/iphone-app-factory/bootstrap.mjs \\\n  --app-dir 'apps/waketask-iphone' \\\n  --app-name 'WakeTask' \\\n  --bundle-id 'com.keen.waketask' \\\n  --boilerplate-repo 'SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro-Distribution'\n```\n\nThis clones/copies `SwiftAIBoilerplatePro-Distribution` into `apps/waketask-iphone` with:\n\n- **SwiftAIBoilerplatePro.xcodeproj** — pre-configured Xcode project\n- **Config/App.xcconfig** — build configurations, target properties\n- All boilerplate **Packages/** intact (Core, Networking, Storage, Auth, Payments, AI, FeatureSettings, Localization, DesignSystem)\n- **CompositionRoot** DI assembly pattern wired in the app entry point\n- SwiftLint, SwiftFormat, Qlty hooks, and CI scaffolding\n\nThe project is then renamed to `WakeTask.xcodeproj` and the bundle ID is set to `com.keen.waketask`. All subsequent architecture decisions **extend — never replace** this base.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Boilerplate Module Map\n\nEvery module listed below remains in the project. None are removed.\n\n| Module | Path | WakeTask Usage |\n|---|---|---|\n| **SwiftAIBoilerplatePro.xcodeproj** | `./WakeTask.xcodeproj` | Project structure, build settings, target definitions — renamed to `WakeTask.xcodeproj` after bootstrap |\n| **Config/App.xcconfig** | `Config/App.xcconfig` | Build configurations for Debug / Release / TestFlight; no edits required beyond bundle ID |\n| **Packages/Core** | `Packages/Core/` | Foundation utilities, extensions, error handling, app lifecycle; WakeTask registers its services into the DI container provided here |\n| **Packages/Networking** | `Packages/Networking/` | HTTP abstractions, interceptors, mock support — unused in MVP alarm flow (offline-first); kept for Social Witness v1.1 |\n| **Packages/Storage** | `Packages/Storage/` | SwiftData integration, persistence patterns — extended with WakeTask entities (AlarmSchedule, SnoozeRecord, DifficultyState, TaskHistory) |\n| **Packages/Auth** | `Packages/Auth/` | Authentication workflows, credential management — used as-is if boilerplate provides onboarding; no custom auth added |\n| **Packages/Payments** | `Packages/Payments/` | StoreKit / RevenueCat integration, entitlement checks — present for future subscription tiers; MVP free tier activates all features |\n| **Packages/AI** | `Packages/AI/` | LLM client abstractions, prompt templates — not used in MVP; kept for future feature parity |\n| **Packages/FeatureSettings** | `Packages/FeatureSettings/` | Settings screen scaffold — extended with WakeTask-specific rows (task toggles, difficulty slider, timer picker, haptic toggle) |\n| **Packages/Localization** | `Packages/Localization/` | String catalog loading, `LocalizedStringKey` helpers, RTL support — all WakeTask strings go through this pipeline |\n| **Packages/DesignSystem** | `Packages/DesignSystem/` | Colors, typography, spacing, buttons, cards — all WakeTask UI composed from these primitives; alarm screen uses high-contrast token overrides |\n| **CompositionRoot** | `CompositionRoot/` | Single DI assembly point — WakeTask services registered via `WakeTaskComposition.swift` extension called at app launch |\n\n### 1.1 Dependency Order\n\n```\nCompositionRoot\n  → Packages/Core            (foundation)\n    → Packages/Storage       (persistence)\n      → WakeTaskData models  (alarm schedule, snooze records, difficulty state)\n    → Packages/Networking    (available, idle in MVP)\n  → Packages/Auth            (as-is)\n  → Packages/Payments        (as-is)\n  → Packages/AI              (as-is, unused)\n  → Packages/FeatureSettings (extended)\n  → Packages/Localization    (as-is)\n  → Packages/DesignSystem    (as-is; alarm tokens added)\n```\n\nAll WakeTask-specific packages (`AlarmScheduler`, `TaskEngine`, `AdaptiveDifficultyEngine`, `ChallengeOrchestrator`, `WakeConfirmationScheduler`) register into the CompositionRoot container and depend on the boilerplate packages above.\n\n---\n\n## 2. How WakeTask Extends the Boilerplate\n\n### 2.1 CompositionRoot Registration\n\n```swift\n// WakeTaskComposition.swift — new file, no boilerplate edits\nextension CompositionRoot {\n    static func registerWakeTaskServices(in container: DIContainer) {\n        container.register(AlarmSchedulerProtocol.self) { _ in AlarmScheduler() }\n        container.register(TaskEngineProtocol.self) { _ in TaskEngine() }\n        container.register(AdaptiveDifficultyEngineProtocol.self) { _ in AdaptiveDifficultyEngine() }\n        container.register(ChallengeOrchestratorProtocol.self) { _ in ChallengeOrchestrator() }\n        container.register(WakeConfirmationSchedulerProtocol.self) { _ in WakeConfirmationScheduler() }\n        // Repositories\n        container.register(AlarmRepository.self) { c in AlarmRepositoryImpl(store: c.resolve(Storage.self)!) }\n        container.register(DifficultyRepository.self) { c in DifficultyRepositoryImpl(store: c.resolve(Storage.self)!) }\n    }\n}\n\n// Called from @main or AppDelegate:\nCompositionRoot.registerWakeTaskServices(in: container)\n```\n\n### 2.2 DesignSystem Usage\n\n| Screen | DesignSystem Components Used | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| Home / Dashboard | `NavigationBar`, `CardView`, `Button.primary`, `Typography` | Shows next alarm, streak, snooze rate |\n| Alarm Schedule Editor | `FeatureSettings` rows, `DatePicker`, `Toggle` | Uses boilerplate settings scaffold |\n| **Alarm Firing (Challenge)** | **No DesignSystem chrome** — raw SwiftUI with high-contrast colors | Per spec: \"zero navigational chrome\" |\n| Math / Motion / Tap / Barcode challenges | `Typography.display`, `Button`, custom progress gauges | All use `DesignSystem.Color` token values |\n| Settings | Entirely `FeatureSettings` package | |\n\n**New tokens** (minimal, semantic only):\n- `DesignSystem/Tokens/AlarmTokens.swift` — `alarmUrgentBackground` (deep black), `alarmHighContrast` (bright yellow/orange for WCAG AAA), haptic pattern constants.\n\n**No new DesignSystem component or layout files are created.** All alarm-mode styling is achieved through inline SwiftUI modifiers using existing DesignSystem token values.\n\n### 2.3 Storage Extension\n\nNew SwiftData entities added **alongside** existing boilerplate models:\n\n| Entity | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `AlarmSchedule` | Local alarm schedule (fire time, enabled, last fired) |\n| `SnoozeRecord` | Per-snooze telemetry (timestamp, escalation level, task modality) |\n| `DifficultyState` | Adaptive difficulty tracker (baseline, current level, streak) |\n| `TaskHistory` | 30-day rolling history for rotation / no-repeat logic |\n\nThese use the same persistence stack and container configuration from `Packages/Storage`.\n\n---\n\n## 3. WakeTask-Specific Modules\n\n### 3.1 AlarmScheduler\n\nWraps `UNUserNotificationCenter` for reliable local notification scheduling. Fully offline.\n\n- `schedule(_ alarm: Alarm) async throws`\n- `cancel(_ alarmId: UUID) async throws`\n- `reschedule(after snooze: TimeInterval) async throws`\n- Implements `UNUserNotificationCenterDelegate` for notification action handling\n\n### 3.2 TaskEngine\n\nPure domain logic — no UI.\n\n- `selectChallenge(context:)` — respects 3-day no-repeat rule, user preferences, adaptive difficulty\n- `validateCompletion(input, against:)` — validates motion, math, pattern, barcode, tap-sequence inputs\n- Challenge types: `.motion`, `.mathPuzzle`, `.patternTap`, `.barcodeLocation`, `.tapSequence`\n\n### 3.3 AdaptiveDifficultyEngine\n\nCalculates difficulty based on snooze patterns:\n\n- snooze rate < 0.1 → decrease difficulty\n- snooze rate 0.1–0.4 → hold steady\n- snooze rate > 0.4 → increase by 1 level\n- Hard ceiling at `.extreme` (level 5); perfect week resets; manual reset always available\n\n### 3.4 ChallengeOrchestrator\n\n`@MainActor` state machine coordinating the full alarm flow:\n\n```\nidle → presentingChallenge → challengeCompleted → postWakeConfirmation → dismissed\n                              ↓\n                         snoozeEscalated → presentingChallenge (escalated)\n                              ↓\n                         emergencyEscape → dismissed (logged)\n```\n\n### 3.5 WakeConfirmationScheduler\n\nSchedules a silent/haptic ping 5 minutes after alarm dismissal. Requires single tap. Missed confirmation re-triggers primary alarm with escalated difficulty.\n\n### 3.6 SocialWitness (Scaffolding — v1.1)\n\nPrivacy-first notification capability. MVP includes UI for adding witnesses (stored locally). Notification delivery deferred.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Swift 6 Concurrency Strategy\n\nAll packages compile with `StrictConcurrency=complete`:\n\n- `AlarmScheduler`, `TaskEngine`, `AdaptiveDifficultyEngine`, `ChallengeOrchestrator`: `@MainActor` singletons\n- All model structs (`Alarm`, `SnoozeRecord`, `DifficultyState`, `TaskHistory`): `Sendable` value types\n- `UNUserNotificationCenter` delegate: immediately hops to `@MainActor` via `Task { @MainActor in ... }`\n- `CMMotionManager` wrapped in an `actor MotionSensor` that publishes filtered values via `AsyncStream`\n- Timer isolation: `ContinuousClock.sleep` in `async let`, cancelled on dismiss; single owner (`ChallengeViewModel`)\n\nFile line budget: all production `.swift` files under **400 lines**. Complex ViewModels split into focused extensions.\n\n---\n\n## 5. File Layout\n\n```\napps/waketask-iphone/\n├── WakeTask.xcodeproj/            # Renamed from SwiftAIBoilerplatePro.xcodeproj\n├── Config/\n│   └── App.xcconfig               # Build configurations (untouched)\n├── Packages/                      # All boilerplate packages — UNCHANGED\n│   ├── Core/\n│   ├── Networking/\n│   ├── Storage/\n│   ├── Auth/\n│   ├── Payments/\n│   ├── AI/\n│   ├── FeatureSettings/           # Extended with AlarmSettingsView\n│   ├── Localization/\n│   └── DesignSystem/              # Extended with AlarmTokens.swift\n├── CompositionRoot/               # Extended via WakeTaskComposition.swift\n├── Sources/\n│   └── Features/\n│       └── WakeTask/\n│           ├── Home/\n│           ├── Alarm/\n│           ├── Challenge/\n│           ├── Difficulty/\n│           ├── Models/\n│           ├── Repositories/\n│           └── Composition/\n│               └── WakeTaskComposition.swift\n├── Tests/WakeTaskTests/\n├── UITests/WakeTaskUITests/\n│   └── ExploratoryMonkeyTester.swift\n├── e2e/appium/                    # Node.js Appium harness\n├── scripts/iphone-app-factory/\n│   ├── string-audit.mjs\n│   └── boilerplate-integrity-check.mjs\n├── .github/workflows/waketask-ci.yml\n├── .swiftlint.yml\n├── .swiftformat\n└── Info.plist                     # Extended with privacy usage strings\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. GitHub macOS CI Pipeline\n\nValidation runs on **GitHub-hosted macOS runners** (`macos-15`), never on local Xcode or simulator.\n\n### 6.1 Workflow Gates (All Blocking)\n\n| Gate | Tool | Blocking? |\n|---|---|---|\n| SwiftLint | `swiftlint --strict` | ✅ Yes |\n| SwiftFormat | `swiftformat --lint` | ✅ Yes |\n| StrictConcurrency | `xcodebuild` with `StrictConcurrency=complete` | ✅ Yes |\n| Qlty complexity | `qlty check` (all files < 400 lines) | ✅ Yes |\n| Secret scanning | `gitleaks` or `secretlint` | ✅ Yes |\n| xcodebuild build | `xcodebuild build` | ✅ Yes |\n| xcodebuild test | `xcodebuild test` | ✅ Yes |\n| Appium exploratory | XCUITest monkey-tapper | ✅ Yes |\n| 4.3 string audit | `string-audit.mjs` | ✅ Yes |\n| Boilerplate integrity | `boilerplate-integrity-check.mjs` | ✅ Yes |\n\n### 6.2 CI Workflow\n\n```yaml\nname: WakeTask CI\non:\n  push:\n    branches: [main, develop]\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_11","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,260p' .workflow/iphone-app-factory/adr.md\"","aggregated_output":"# WakeTask Architectural Decision Record\n\n**App**: WakeTask (com.keen.waketask)  \n**Date**: 2026-05-14  \n**Boilerplate**: SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro-Distribution  \n**Status**: Accepted\n\n---\n\n## ADR-001: Extend SwiftAIBoilerplatePro — Do Not Rebuild Platform Infrastructure\n\n**Decision**: WakeTask extends `SwiftAIBoilerplatePro` exclusively. No core platform components (Authentication, Networking, Storage, Payments, AI, Localization, FeatureSettings, DesignSystem) are rebuilt within the application boundary.\n\n**Rationale**:\n- The quality bar (`quality-bar.json`) explicitly forbids rebuilding auth, payments, AI, storage, networking, localization, settings, or design system without ADR approval.\n- The product spec states: \"The application MUST forcefully leverage the `SwiftAIBoilerplatePro` repository. Rebuilding core infrastructure is strictly forbidden.\"\n- Boilerplate modules are production-tested; modifying them risks cascading bugs and breaks the update path for future boilerplate releases.\n- Compliance is validated via a CI-blocking `boilerplate-integrity-check.mjs` script that scans for redundant implementations.\n\n**Alternatives Considered**:\n- Partial rebuild of Networking and Auth: Rejected — WakeTask has no custom auth or networking requirements; the boilerplate already provides these.\n- Fork the boilerplate: Rejected — forking breaks the extension model and makes boilerplate updates impossible.\n\n---\n\n## ADR-002: Keep All Boilerplate Modules Intact — No Removals\n\n**Decision**: All boilerplate packages remain in the project:\n\n| Module | Status | Justification |\n|---|---|---|\n| `Packages/Core` | Kept | Foundation utilities required by all other modules |\n| `Packages/Networking` | Kept (idle in MVP) | Needed for Social Witness v1.1; removal would destabilize SPM graph |\n| `Packages/Storage` | Kept (extended) | WakeTask entities share the boilerplate persistence stack |\n| `Packages/Auth` | Kept | Used as-is; no custom auth layer |\n| `Packages/Payments` | Kept (idle in MVP) | Future subscription tiers rely on this; zero overhead cost |\n| `Packages/AI` | Kept (idle in MVP) | Future feature parity; no measurable binary-size penalty |\n| `Packages/FeatureSettings` | Kept (extended) | Extended with `AlarmSettingsView` |\n| `Packages/Localization` | Kept | All WakeTask strings go through this pipeline |\n| `Packages/DesignSystem` | Kept (extended) | All WakeTask UI composed from these primitives |\n| `CompositionRoot` | Kept (extended) | WakeTask services registered via `WakeTaskComposition.swift` |\n| `SwiftAIBoilerplatePro.xcodeproj` | Kept (renamed) | Renamed to `WakeTask.xcodeproj` after bootstrap |\n| `Config/App.xcconfig` | Kept | Build configurations left intact |\n\n**App Store 4.3 Consequence**: Removing boilerplate modules would reduce the app's codebase to a minimal alarm utility — structurally similar to alarm apps already on the App Store. By retaining the full boilerplate surface area (payments, AI, auth, networking, design system, localization), WakeTask presents itself as a **full-featured platform app**, not a single-purpose widget. This, combined with the behavioral psychology differentiators in metadata, materially reduces 4.3 spam-rejection risk.\n\n**Dependency Order Impact**: If any module were removed:\n- Removing `Networking` would require Social Witness v1.1 to introduce its own network client — a direct violation of ADR-001.\n- Removing `DesignSystem` would force all WakeTask UI to use raw SwiftUI, losing WCAG AAA accessibility guarantees and visual consistency.\n- Removing `Storage` would mean rebuilding the SwiftData stack — the largest single violation of ADR-001.\n- Removing `CompositionRoot` would break the DI pattern, forcing ad-hoc instantiation and making test injection impossible.\n\n**Alternatives Considered**:\n- Remove `Packages/AI` to reduce compile time: Rejected — Swift Packages that contribute unused symbols have negligible binary-size or compile-time overhead. Keeping the package preserves the future feature path and avoids altering the SPM dependency graph.\n\n---\n\n## ADR-003: WakeTask Modules Added Through CompositionRoot\n\n**Decision**: All WakeTask-specific services are registered as extensions to the boilerplate's `CompositionRoot` DI container. The pattern is:\n\n1. Create `WakeTaskComposition.swift` (new file, no boilerplate edits).\n2. Define `extension CompositionRoot { static func registerWakeTaskServices(in:) }`.\n3. Call `CompositionRoot.registerWakeTaskServices(in: container)` from `@main` or `AppDelegate`.\n\n**Rationale**:\n- Preserves the boilerplate's established DI pattern.\n- Zero edits to boilerplate source files.\n- WakeTask ViewModels receive dependencies via protocol types — consistent with MVVM.\n- The router/navigation structure is extended, not replaced: WakeTask's `HomeView` / `AlarmView` becomes the default root destination.\n\n---\n\n## ADR-004: Setup/Acquisition Before Implementation\n\n**Decision**: The boilerplate **must** be acquired into `apps/waketask-iphone` before any WakeTask-specific code is written. This is done via:\n\n```bash\nnode scripts/iphone-app-factory/bootstrap.mjs \\\n  --app-dir 'apps/waketask-iphone' \\\n  --app-name 'WakeTask' \\\n  --bundle-id 'com.keen.waketask' \\\n  --boilerplate-repo 'SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro-Distribution'\n```\n\nThe scratch `apps/waketask-iphone` directory is empty at project start. The bootstrap script clones/copies the boilerplate distribution, renames the Xcode project, updates the bundle ID, and validates that all packages are intact.\n\n**Rationale**: Without the bootstrap step, there is no project structure, no package dependencies, and no CI scaffolding to build upon.\n\n---\n\n## ADR-005: GitHub-Hosted macOS CI Validation Only\n\n**Decision**: All build, test, and validation gates execute on **GitHub-hosted macOS runners** (`macos-15`). Local Xcode builds and local simulator runs are not considered evidence of completion.\n\n**Blocking gates on CI**:\n- `xcodebuild build` succeeds\n- `xcodebuild test` passes\n- SwiftLint zero violations\n- SwiftFormat clean\n- Qlty complexity (all files < 400 lines)\n- Secret scanning zero violations\n- Appium / XCUITest exploratory tapper passes\n- App Store 4.3 string audit passes\n- Boilerplate integrity check passes\n\n**Rationale**: The quality bar mandates CI evidence. Only the hosted macOS lane is reproducible and auditable by the factory framework.\n\n---\n\n## ADR-006: `UNUserNotificationCenter` for Alarm Scheduling\n\n**Decision**: Alarm scheduling uses Apple's `UNUserNotificationCenter` exclusively. No custom background services or background audio for alarm triggering.\n\n**Rationale**:\n- iOS does not allow third-party apps to execute arbitrary code at a specific time in the background.\n- `UNUserNotificationCenter` is the only Apple-approved mechanism for time-triggered events.\n- The alarm fires as a local notification; tapping the notification opens the app into `ChallengeView`.\n- Fully offline — no server round-trip required.\n\n---\n\n## ADR-007: Challenge Modalities and Accessibility\n\n**Decision**: MVP includes four challenge types with universal tap-fallback:\n\n| Challenge | Input | Fallback |\n|---|---|---|\n| Motion (shake) | `CMMotionManager` accelerometer | Tap sequence (5 taps) |\n| Math puzzle | Numeric text field | Tap sequence |\n| Pattern/tap | Grid tap sequence | Tap sequence (inherent) |\n| Barcode/location | `AVFoundation` camera | Tap sequence |\n\nEvery challenge has a non-visual accessibility path (haptic-only or tap-only mode).\n\n**Deferred to v1.1**: Voice/audio confirmation task (unreliable in MVP; spec marks as optional).\n\n---\n\n## ADR-008: Social Witness Privacy-First Scaffolding\n\n**Decision**: The Social Witness feature is scaffolded in MVP (UI for adding witnesses, local storage of witness profiles) but notification delivery is deferred to v1.1.\n\n**Privacy Guarantees**:\n- Witness profiles stored locally only (no cloud sync).\n- No location data, no time-of-day, no sleep duration transmitted.\n- Notification content is minimal: \"Your friend oversleep streak: N days.\"\n\n**Rationale**: Complex privacy/notification coordination requires additional review. The spec marks Social Witness as optional for MVP.\n\n---\n\n## ADR-009: File Line Budget — 400 Lines Maximum\n\n**Decision**: All production Swift files stay under 400 lines. Complex ViewModels are split into focused extension files (e.g., `ChallengeViewModel.swift`, `ChallengeViewModel+MathTask.swift`, `ChallengeViewModel+MotionTask.swift`).\n\n**Enforcement**: `wc -l` check in CI pipeline; Qlty complexity check is blocking.\n\n---\n\n## ADR-010: Swift 6 Strict Concurrency\n\n**Decision**: The project compiles with `StrictConcurrency=complete`. All concurrency warnings are treated as errors.\n\n- `@MainActor` on all ViewModels and orchestrators.\n- `Sendable` on all model structs.\n- `actor` isolation for `CMMotionManager` wrapper.\n- `UNUserNotificationCenter` delegate immediately hops to `@MainActor`.\n\n---\n\n## Summary of All Decisions\n\n| ADR | Decision | Impact on Boilerplate | Status |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| ADR-001 | Extend SwiftAIBoilerplatePro — no rebuilds | All packages kept | Accepted |\n| ADR-002 | Keep all boilerplate modules — no removals | Core, Networking, Storage, Auth, Payments, AI, FeatureSettings, Localization, DesignSystem, CompositionRoot, SwiftAIBoilerplatePro.xcodeproj, Config/App.xcconfig all intact | Accepted |\n| ADR-003 | WakeTask modules via CompositionRoot | New `WakeTaskComposition.swift` extends container | Accepted |\n| ADR-004 | Bootstrap before implementation | `apps/waketask-iphone` populated by bootstrap script | Accepted |\n| ADR-005 | GitHub-hosted macOS CI only | CI workflow targets `macos-15` | Accepted |\n| ADR-006 | UNUserNotificationCenter for alarms | No new background services | Accepted |\n| ADR-007 | Challenge modalities with accessibility fallbacks | No boilerplate changes | Accepted |\n| ADR-008 | Social Witness scaffolded, delivery v1.1 | No boilerplate changes | Accepted |\n| ADR-009 | 400-line file budget | Enforcement via CI gate | Accepted |\n| ADR-010 | Swift 6 strict concurrency | Build setting `StrictConcurrency=complete` | Accepted |\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
